GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 514
Short Title: APRN Definitions. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives White, Lambeth, Setzer, and Cunningham (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Health, if favorable, Judiciary 1, if favorable, Finance, if favorable, Rules,
Calendar, and Operations of the House
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO DEFINE THE PRACTICE OF NURSING FOR ADVANCED PRACTICE
3 REGISTERED NURSES: NURSE PRACTITIONERS (NP), CERTIFIED NURSE
4 MIDWIVES (CNM), CERTIFIED REGISTERED NURSE ANESTHETISTS (CRNA),
5 AND CLINICAL NURSE SPECIALISTS (CNS).
6 Whereas, North Carolina is expected to be the seventh largest state in the nation by
7 2035 and demand for health care will continue to increase; and
8 Whereas, North Carolina has provided over 628,000 North Carolinians access to
9 insurance through Medicaid expansion but lacks the health care providers to ensure their access
10 to care; and
11 Whereas, APRNs are registered nurses with master's or doctorate degrees and
12 advanced education and training; and
13 Whereas, North Carolina has over 20,000 advanced practice registered nurses
14 (APRNs) who have been educated and licensed to practice to their full scope; and
15 Whereas, more than three decades of research demonstrates that APRNs improve
16 access to safe, high-quality, cost-effective, patient-centered health care; and
17 Whereas, the Institute of Medicine (IOM) has called for states to allow APRNs to
18 practice to the full extent of their licensure and education since the 2010 release of the IOM
19 Report on the Future of Nursing; and
20 Whereas, health care costs in North Carolina are among the highest in the nation; and
21 Whereas, a recent report by a Ph.D. health care economist at Duke University
22 estimates savings of at least $700 million annually for North Carolina patients, employers, and
23 taxpayers by removing unnecessary and antiquated government regulations; and
24 Whereas, 36 other states have rolled back these costly and burdensome government
25 regulations on advanced practice registered nurses over the past 31 years with no evidence of
26 negative effects on patient safety, and indeed positive impact on patient care, according to
27 numerous studies; and
28 Whereas, no state has enacted these reforms and later reversed course to reinstate
29 these government regulations; and
30 Whereas, the APRN role has existed for over a half century but remains undefined in
31 North Carolina statute; and
32 Whereas, North Carolina's courts and executive branch have called on the legislature,
33 the body of the people, to remove the ambiguity surrounding APRN practice by clearly defining
34 it in statute; Now, therefore,
*H514-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
2 SECTION 1. G.S. 90-171.20 reads as rewritten:
3 "§ 90-171.20. Definitions.
4 As used in this Article, unless the context requires otherwise:
5 (1) Advanced assessment. – The taking by an advanced practice registered nurse
6 of the history, physical, and psychological assessment of a patient's signs,
7 symptoms, pathophysiologic status, and psychosocial variations in the
8 determination of differential diagnoses and treatment.
9 (1a) Advanced practice registered nurse or APRN. – An individual licensed by the
10 Board as an advanced practice registered nurse within one of the following
11 four roles:
12 a. Certified nurse practitioner or CNP.
13 b. Certified nurse midwife or CNM.
14 c. Clinical nurse specialist or CNS.
15 d. Certified registered nurse anesthetist or CRNA.
16 (1b) "Board" means the Board. – The North Carolina Board of Nursing.
17 (2) "Health care provider" means any Health care provider. – Any licensed health
18 care professional and any agent or employee of any health care institution,
19 health care insurer, health care professional school, or a member of any allied
20 health profession. For purposes of this Article, a person enrolled in a program
21 that prepares the person to be a licensed health care professional or an allied
22 health professional shall be deemed a health care provider.
23 (3) "License" means a License. – A permit issued by the Board to practice nursing
24 as an advanced practice registered nurse, as a registered nurse nurse, or as a
25 licensed practical nurse, including a renewal or reinstatement thereof.
26 (3a) "Licensee" means any Licensee. – Any person issued a license by the Board,
27 whether the license is active or inactive, including an inactive license by
28 means of surrender.
29 (4) "Nursing" is a Nursing. – A dynamic discipline which includes the assessing,
30 caring, counseling, teaching, referring and implementing of prescribed
31 treatment in the maintenance of health, prevention and management of illness,
32 injury, disability or the achievement of a dignified death. It is ministering to;
33 assisting; and sustained, vigilant, and continuous care of those acutely or
34 chronically ill; supervising patients during convalescence and rehabilitation;
35 the supportive and restorative care given to maintain the optimum health level
36 of individuals, groups, and communities; the supervision, teaching, and
37 evaluation of those who perform or are preparing to perform these functions;
38 and the administration of nursing programs and nursing services. For purposes
39 of this Article, the administration of required lethal substances or any
40 assistance whatsoever rendered with an execution under Article 19 of Chapter
41 15 of the General Statutes does not constitute nursing.
42 (5) "Nursing program" means any Nursing program. – Any educational program
43 in North Carolina offering to prepare persons to meet the educational
44 requirements for licensure under this Article.Article as a registered nurse or a
45 licensed practical nurse.
46 (6) "Person" means an Person. – An individual, corporation, partnership,
47 association, unit of government, or other legal entity.
48 (6a) Population focus. – With respect to APRN practice, includes one of the
49 following areas of focus:
50 a. The family or the individual across the life span.
51 b. Adult/gerontology.
Page 2 House Bill 514-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c. Neonatal.
2 d. Pediatrics.
3 e. Women's health or gender-related issues.
4 f. Psychiatric mental health.
5 (6b) Practice of nursing as a certified nurse midwife or CNM. – In addition to the
6 RN scope of practice and APRN role and population foci, also consists of the
7 following four components:
8 a. The management, diagnosis, and treatment of primary sexual and
9 reproductive health care, including primary, preconception,
10 gynecologic/reproductive/sexual health, antepartum, intrapartum,
11 neonatal, and post-pregnancy care.
12 b. Ordering, performing, supervising, and interpreting diagnostic studies.
13 c. Prescribing pharmacologic and nonpharmacologic therapies.
14 d. Consulting with or referring to other health care providers as
15 warranted by the needs of the patient.
16 (6c) Practice of nursing as a certified nurse practitioner or CNP. – In addition to
17 the RN scope of practice and APRN role and population foci, also consists of
18 the following six components:
19 a. Health promotion, disease prevention, health education, and
20 counseling.
21 b. Providing health assessment and screening activities.
22 c. Diagnosing, treating, and facilitating patients' management of their
23 acute and chronic illnesses and diseases.
24 d. Ordering, performing, supervising, and interpreting diagnostic studies.
25 e. Prescribing pharmacologic and nonpharmacologic therapies.
26 f. Consulting with or referring to other health care providers as
27 warranted by the needs of the patient.
28 (6d) Practice of nursing as a certified registered nurse anesthetist or CRNA. – In
29 addition to the RN scope of practice and within the APRN role and population
30 foci, also consists of the following:
31 a. Selecting, ordering, procuring, prescribing, and administering drugs
32 and therapeutic devices to facilitate diagnostic, therapeutic, and
33 surgical procedures.
34 b. Ordering, prescribing, performing, supervising, and interpreting
35 diagnostic studies, procedures, and interventions.
36 c. Consulting with or referring to other health care providers as
37 warranted by the needs of the patient.
38 (6e) Practice of nursing as a clinical nurse specialist or CNS. – In addition to the
39 RN scope of practice and APRN role and population foci, also consists of the
40 following eight components:
41 a. The diagnosis and treatment of health and illness states.
42 b. Disease management.
43 c. Prescribing pharmacologic and nonpharmacologic therapies.
44 d. Ordering, performing, supervising, and interpreting diagnostic studies.
45 e. Preventing of illness and risk behaviors.
46 f. Nursing care for individuals, families, and communities.
47 g. Integrating care across the continuum to improve patient outcomes.
48 h. Consulting with or referring to other health care providers as
49 warranted by the needs of the patient.
House Bill 514-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (6f) Practice of nursing as an advanced practice registered nurse or APRN. – In
2 addition to the RN scope of practice and within the APRN role and population
3 foci, also consists of the following six components:
4 a. Conducting an advanced assessment.
5 b. Delegating and assigning therapeutic measures to assistive personnel.
6 c. Performing other acts that require education and training consistent
7 with professional standards and commensurate with the APRN's
8 education, certification, demonstrated competencies, and experience.
9 d. Complying with the requirements of this Article and rendering quality
10 advanced nursing care.
11 e. Recognizing limits of knowledge and experience.
12 f. Planning for the management of situations beyond the APRN's
13 expertise.
14 (7) The "practice of nursing by a registered nurse" consists Practice of nursing by
15 a registered nurse. – Consists of the following 10 components:
16 a. Assessing the patient's physical and mental health, including the
17 patient's reaction to illnesses and treatment regimens.
18 b. Recording and reporting the results of the nursing assessment.
19 c. Planning, initiating, delivering, and evaluating appropriate nursing
20 acts.
21 d. Teaching, assigning, delegating to or supervising other personnel in
22 implementing the treatment regimen.
23 e. Collaborating with other health care providers in determining the
24 appropriate health care for a patient but, subject to the provisions of
25 G.S. 90-18.2, not prescribing a medical treatment regimen or making
26 a medical diagnosis, except under supervision of a licensed
27 physician.patient.
28 f. Implementing the treatment and pharmaceutical regimen prescribed or
29 ordered by any person authorized by State law to prescribe or order
30 the regimen.
31 g. Providing teaching and counseling about the patient's health.
32 h. Reporting and recording the plan for care, nursing care given, and the
33 patient's response to that care.
34 i. Supervising, teaching, and evaluating those who perform or are
35 preparing to perform nursing functions and administering nursing
36 programs and nursing services.
37 j. Providing for the maintenance of safe and effective nursing care,
38 whether rendered directly or indirectly.
39 (8) The "practice of nursing by a licensed practical nurse" consists of the
40 following seven components:
41 a. Participating in the assessment of the patient's physical and mental
42 health, including the patient's reaction to illnesses and treatment
43 regimens.
44 b. Recording and reporting the results of the nursing assessment.
45 c. Participating in implementing the health care plan developed by the
46 registered nurse and/or prescribed by any person authorized by State
47 law to prescribe such a plan, by performing tasks assigned or delegated
48 by and performed under the supervision or under orders or directions
49 of a registered nurse, physician licensed to practice medicine, dentist,
50 or other person authorized by State law to provide the supervision.
Page 4 House Bill 514-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c1. Assigning or delegating nursing interventions to other qualified
2 personnel under the supervision of the registered nurse.
3 d. Participating in the teaching and counseling of patients as assigned by
4 a registered nurse, physician, or other qualified professional licensed
5 to practice in North Carolina.
6 e. Reporting and recording the nursing care rendered and the patient's
7 response to that care.
8 f. Maintaining safe and effective nursing care, whether rendered directly
9 or indirectly."
