19 SECTION 8. G.S. 90-171.43 reads as rewritten:
20 "§ 90-171.43. License required.
21 (a) No person shall practice or offer to practice as a an advanced practice registered nurse,
22 registered nurse nurse, or licensed practical nurse, or use the word "nurse" as a title for herself or
23 himself, or use an abbreviation to indicate that the person is a an advanced practice registered
24 nurse, registered nurse nurse, or licensed practical nurse, unless the person is currently licensed
25 as a an advanced practice registered nurse, registered nurse nurse, or licensed practical nurse as
26 provided by this Article. If the word "nurse" is part of a longer title, such as "nurse's aide", a
27 person who is entitled to use that title shall use the entire title and may not abbreviate the title to
28 "nurse". This Article shall not, however, be construed to prohibit or limit the following:
29 (1) The performance by any person of any act for which that person holds a
30 license issued pursuant to North Carolina law;law.
31 (2) The clinical practice by students enrolled in approved nursing programs,
32 continuing education programs, or refresher courses under the supervision of
33 qualified faculty;faculty.
34 (3) The performance of nursing performed by persons who hold a temporary
35 license issued pursuant to G.S. 90-171.33;G.S. 90-171.33.
36 (4) The delegation to any person, including a member of the patient's family, by
37 a physician licensed to practice medicine in North Carolina, a licensed dentist
38 or registered nurse of those patient-care services which are routine, repetitive,
39 limited in scope that do not require the professional judgment of a registered
40 nurse or licensed practical nurse;nurse.
41 (5) Assistance by any person in the case of emergency.
42 Any person permitted to practice nursing without a license as provided in subdivision (2)
43 (a)(2) or (3) (a)(3) of this section shall be held to the same standard of care as any licensed nurse.
44 (a1) The abbreviations for the APRN designation of a certified nurse midwife, a clinical
45 nurse specialist, a certified registered nurse anesthetist, and a certified nurse practitioner shall be
46 APRN, plus the role title, i.e., CNM, CNS, CRNA, and CNP.
47 (a2) It shall be unlawful for any person to use the title "APRN" or "APRN" plus their
48 respective role titles, the role title alone, authorized abbreviations, or any other title that would
49 lead a person to believe the individual is an APRN, unless permitted by this act.
50 …."
